Maine elected seven Democratic-Republicans to the Nineteenth Congress.
Five of those Democratic-Republicans were part of a faction led by John
Quincy Adams and Henry Clay.

Maine used a district system for electing members to Congress.

In 1826, a [special
election](https://elections.lib.tufts.edu/catalog/tufts:me.uscongress5.second.1826)
was held in which James W. Ripley was elected to replace Enoch Lincoln,
who had been elected Governor of Maine.
